<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Chirac_au_Quebec.jpg" class="image" title="Humorous cartoon from the French newspaper Le Canard Enchaîné, featuring Jacques Chirac and his wife discussing Quebec French profanity. The title reads: On vacation in Quebec. Chirac's wife Bernadette says: Jacques, why do you always say &quot;chalice&quot; and &quot;tabernacle&quot;?"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/01/Chirac_au_Quebec.jpg/180px-Chirac_au_Quebec.jpg" width="180" height="194" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Chirac_au_Quebec.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Humorous cartoon from the French newspaper <a href="/wiki/Le_Canard_Encha%C3%AEn%C3%A9" title="Le Canard Enchaîné" class="mw-redirect">Le Canard Enchaîné</a>, featuring <a href="/wiki/Jacques_Chirac" title="Jacques Chirac">Jacques Chirac</a> and his wife discussing Quebec French profanity. The title reads: <i>On vacation in Quebec</i>. Chirac's wife Bernadette says: <i>Jacques, why do you always say "chalice" and "tabernacle"?</i></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The literal translation of the <a href="/wiki/French_language" title="French language">French</a> verb <i><b>sacrer</b></i> is "to consecrate". However, in <a href="/wiki/Quebec" title="Quebec">Quebec</a> it is the proper word for the form of <b><a href="/wiki/Profanity" title="Profanity">profanity</a></b> used in <b><a href="/wiki/Quebec_French" title="Quebec French">Quebec French</a></b>. The noun form is <i>sacre</i>.</p>
<p>Quebec French, a variety of <a href="/wiki/Canadian_French" title="Canadian French">Canadian French</a>, uses a number of the same types of foul language as in standard French, dealing with sex and excrement (such as <i>merde</i>, "<a href="/wiki/Shit" title="Shit">shit</a>", which is almost always pronounced <i>marde</i> in Quebec French). These are usually rather mild, and stronger profanity is expressed using words and expressions related to <a href="/wiki/Catholicism" title="Catholicism">Catholicism</a> and its <a href="/wiki/Liturgy" title="Liturgy">liturgy</a>. This usage of religious words to express profanity is also present but to a lesser extent in <a href="/wiki/Acadian_French" title="Acadian French">Acadian French</a>, mostly spoken in the <a href="/wiki/Maritime_provinces" title="Maritime provinces" class="mw-redirect">Maritime provinces</a> east of Quebec.</p>
